                  Solver Explanation 



payload1 = flat(
    b&quot;A&quot; * 0x10,
    b&quot;B&quot; * 0x4,
    p32(bss),
    p32(winner),
)
The first argument is copied into:
strcpy(i1-&gt;name, argv[1]);
Since i1-&gt;name only has 8 bytes, anything longer than that will overflow into the next heap chunk.
To understand the payload, we can map the heap layout like this:
[ i1-&gt;name chunk ][ i2 struct ]
                 [ priority ][ name ][ callback ]
Breakdown:

b&quot;A&quot; * 0x10
This fills:

8 bytes of i1-&gt;name
8 bytes of the next chunk header



After that, the write reaches the fields inside i2.

b&quot;B&quot; * 0x4
This overwrites:

int priority;
inside i2

p32(bss)
This overwrites:

char *name;
inside i2, so when the second strcpy() runs, it writes into .bss

p32(winner)
This overwrites:

void (*callback)();
inside i2, replacing it with the address of winner()
So the overwrite path is:
8 bytes   -&gt; fill i1-&gt;name
8 bytes   -&gt; pass the next chunk header
4 bytes   -&gt; overwrite i2-&gt;priority
4 bytes   -&gt; overwrite i2-&gt;name with .bss
4 bytes   -&gt; overwrite i2-&gt;callback with winner
Which is why the payload is arranged exactly in that order.
Then the program executes:
strcpy(i2-&gt;name, argv[2]);
Since i2-&gt;name now points to .bss, this write succeeds safely.
Finally:
if (i2-&gt;callback) i2-&gt;callback();
and because i2-&gt;callback now contains winner, execution is redirected to winner(), which prints the flag.


